    "blogs": [],
    "aboutText": "## Overall vibe and location\n\nFort Lee is a bustling, highly sought-after borough that feels much like a city due to its dense, built-up downtown. Its prime location, a five-minute walk to the George Washington Bridge, makes it a popular home for commuters who work in Manhattan. It is a highly walkable town with a rich history, having been a major hub for the film industry before Hollywood was established.\n\n## The real estate market\n\nReal estate in Fort Lee is expensive, competitive, and highly desirable.\n\n- **Single-family homes** are the most desirable. Older fixer-upper homes start around $700,000. In highly coveted areas like Abbott Boulevard, older ranch homes sell for the land value alone, so buyers can tear them down and build large new houses.\n- **Luxury homes** in the Bluff section in the southeast part of town feature massive, multi-million-dollar homes, some on lots with unobstructed views of the NYC skyline.\n- **Townhouses and duplexes** are becoming very popular because they require zero yard maintenance. New construction ranges from $1.5 million to the low $2 millions.\n- **Apartments and co-ops** are the cheapest options and sell immediately. Co-ops can be purchased for around $150,000 to $200,000, but they come with massive HOA fees ranging from $1,500 to $4,000 a month.\n- **High-rise rentals** like The Modern and Hudson Lights are rental-only, with a one-bedroom costing roughly $4,000 to $5,000 a month.\n\n## Dining and shopping\n\nFort Lee is a major foodie destination with a wide variety of cuisines, heavily defined by its strong Asian and old-school Italian influences.\n\n- **Downtown and Hudson Lights** features modern plazas with open lawns, the iPic theater, a golf simulator, and heavy concentrations of Korean, Japanese, and Chinese restaurants, plus places like Paris Baguette and Ventanas (a high-end restaurant).\n- **The Linwood and Anderson Avenue area** is home to H Mart (a massive Korean supermarket) and Cafasso's Fairway Market, a beloved local Italian grocer known for fresh produce, an elite butcher counter, and fresh-squeezed orange juice.\n- **Local staples** include Mood Food for healthy eating, Los Compadres for Mexican, and Hiram's, an iconic hot dog stand that has been operating for over 70 years.\n\n## Parks and scenery\n\nFort Lee has incredible scenery, especially at Palisades Interstate Park. The park sits right on the water, offering unobstructed views of the Manhattan skyline. Visitors can walk, take their dogs, and even drive on a road that passes directly underneath the George Washington Bridge.\n\n## The drawbacks\n\nThe main negative is traffic. Because of its proximity to the George Washington Bridge and New York City, the town experiences severe congestion, aggressive driving, and heavy traffic jams, especially during rush hour. The overall cost of living and housing is also a barrier for many.\n\n## Looking ahead\n\nA lot of people think Fort Lee is a city, but it is a borough. Constant development is shaping Fort Lee into one of the most cutting-edge and forward-thinking municipalities in Bergen County. And its access to the city is unrivaled.",
